[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Extendible hashing was described by Ronald Fagin in 1979.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Practically all modern filesystems use either extendible hashing or B-trees.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] In particular, the Global File System, GPFS, ZFS, and the SpadFS filesystem use extendible hashing.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Assume that the hash function $h(k)$ returns a string of bits.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] The first i bits of each string will be used as indices to figure out where they will go in the "directory" (hash table), where i is the smallest number such that the index of every item in the table is unique.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Now, if k3 were to be hashed to the table, it wouldn't be enough to distinguish all three keys by one bit (because both k3 and k1 have 1 as their leftmost bit).
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Also, because the bucket size is one, the table would overflow.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] And so now k1 and k3 have a unique location, being distinguished by the first two leftmost bits.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Because k2 is in the top half of the table, both 00 and 01 point to it because there is no other key to compare to that begins with a 0.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Now, k4 needs to be inserted, and it has the first two bits as 01..(1110), and using a 2 bit depth in the directory, this maps from 01 to Bucket A.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Bucket A is full (max size 1), so it must be split; because there is more than one pointer to Bucket A, there is no need to increase the directory size.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Examining the initial case of an extendible hash structure, if each directory entry points to one bucket, then the local depth should be equal to the global depth.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] The number of directory entries is equal to 2global depth, and the initial number of buckets is equal to 2local depth.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Thus if global depth = local depth = 0, then 20 = 1, so an initial directory of one pointer to one bucket.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] If the local depth is less than the global depth, then there exists more than one pointer from the directory to the bucket, and the bucket can be split.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Key 01 points to Bucket A, and Bucket A's local depth of 1 is less than the directory's global depth of 2, which means keys hashed to Bucket A have only used a 1 bit prefix (i.e.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] If ⁠ $k_{2}$ ⁠ had been 000110, with key 00, there would have been no problem, because ⁠ $k_{2}$ ⁠ would have remained in the new bucket A' and bucket D would have been empty.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] (This would have been the most likely case by far when buckets are of greater size than 1 and the newly split buckets would be exceedingly unlikely to overflow, unless all the entries were all rehashed to one bucket again.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] So Bucket D needs to be split, but a check of its local depth, which is 2, is the same as the global depth, which is 2, so the directory must be split again, in order to hold keys of sufficient detail, e.g.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] As D's local depth = the global depth, the directory must double to increase bit detail of keys.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Global depth has incremented after directory split to 3.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] The new entry ⁠ $k_{4}$ ⁠ is rekeyed with global depth 3 bits and ends up in D which has local depth 2, which can now be incremented to 3 and D can be split to D' and E.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] The contents of the split bucket D, ⁠ $k_{2}$ ⁠, has been re-keyed with 3 bits, and it ends up in D'.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] K4 is retried and it ends up in E which has a spare slot.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Below is the extendible hashing algorithm in Python, with the disc block / memory page association, caching and consistency issues removed.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] Note a problem exists if the depth exceeds the bit size of an integer, because then doubling of the directory or splitting of a bucket won't allow entries to be rehashed to different buckets.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/extendible-hashing] The code uses the *least significant bits*, which makes it more efficient to expand the table, as the entire directory can be copied as one block (Ramakrishnan & Gehrke (2003)).
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] In computer science, a **grid file** or **bucket grid** is a point access method which splits a space into a non-periodic grid where one or more cells of the grid refer to a small set of points.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] Grid files (a symmetric data structure) provide an efficient method of storing these indexes on disk to perform complex data lookups.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] It provides a grid of *n*-dimensions where *n* represents how many keys can be used to reference a single point.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] Grid files do not contain any data themselves but instead contain references to the correct bucket.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] A grid file is usually used in cases where a single value can be referenced by multiple keys.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] A grid file began being used because "traditional file structures that provide multikey access to records, for example, inverted files, are extensions of file structures originally designed for single-key access.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] In a traditional single dimensional data structure (e.g. hash), a search on a single criterion is usually very simple but searching for a second criterion can be much more complex.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] Grid files represent a special kind of hashing, where the traditional hash is replaced by a grid directory.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] Consider a database containing data from a census.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] A single record represents a single household, and all records are grouped into buckets.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] All records in a bucket can be indexed by either their city (which is the same for all records in the bucket), and the streets in that city whose names begin with the same letter.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] A grid file can be used to provide an efficient index for this structure, where records come in groupings of 26, each of them relating to street names in a city starting with one of the letters of the alphabet.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] This structure can be thought of as an array, table, or grid with two dimensions which we will call the x and y axes.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] One may consider the x-axis to be the city and the y-axis to be each of the letters in the alphabet, or alternatively, the first letter of each street.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] Each record in this structure is known as a cell.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] Each cell will contain a pointer to the appropriate bucket in the database where the actual data is stored.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] An extra cell, or record header, may be required to store the name of the city.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] Other cells grouped with it will only need to contain the pointer to their respective bucket, since the first cell corresponds to street names beginning with "A", the second to "B", and so on.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] The database can be further extended to contain a continent field to expand the census to other continents.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] This would cause records in the same bucket to correspond to households on a street beginning with the same letter, in the same city, in the same continent.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/grid-file] The cells in the grid file would then consist of a city header, and six (one for each continent, not including Antarctica) groupings of 26 cells relating to the streets with the same starting letter, in the same city, on the same continent and could now be thought of as a three-dimensional array.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In computer science, a **hash table** is a data structure that implements an associative array, also called a **dictionary** or simply **map**; an associative array is an abstract data type that maps keys to values.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A hash table uses a hash function to compute an *index*, also called a *hash code*, into an array of *buckets* or *slots*, from which the desired value can be found.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] During lookup, the key is hashed and the resulting hash indicates where the corresponding value is stored.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A map implemented by a hash table is called a **hash map**.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Most hash table designs employ an imperfect hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hash collisions, where the hash function generates the same index for more than one key, therefore typically must be accommodated in some way.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Common strategies to handle hash collisions include chaining, which stores multiple elements in the same slot using linked lists, and open addressing, which searches for the next available slot according to a probing sequence.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In a well-dimensioned hash table, the average time complexity for each lookup is independent of the number of elements stored in the table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Many hash table designs also allow arbitrary insertions and deletions of key–value pairs, at amortized constant average cost per operation.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hashing is an example of a space–time tradeoff.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] If memory is infinite, the entire key can be used directly as an index to locate its value with a single memory access.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] On the other hand, if infinite time is available, values can be stored without regard for their keys, and a binary search or linear search can be used to retrieve the element.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In many situations, hash tables turn out to be on average more efficient than search trees or any other table lookup structure.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] For this reason, they are widely used in many kinds of computer software, particularly for associative arrays, database indexing, caches, and sets.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Many programming languages provide built-in hash table structures, such as Python’s dictionaries, Java’s HashMap, C++’s unordered_map, Go maps, which abstract the complexity of hashing from the programmer.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The idea of hashing arose independently in different places.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In January 1953, Hans Peter Luhn wrote an internal IBM memorandum that used hashing with chaining.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The first example of open addressing was proposed by A.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Around the same time, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research implemented hashing for the IBM 701 assembler.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Open addressing with linear probing is credited to Amdahl, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The term "open addressing" was coined by W.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Wesley Peterson in his article which discusses the problem of search in large files.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The first published work on hashing with chaining is credited to Arnold Dumey, who discussed the idea of using remainder modulo a prime as a hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The word "hashing" was first published in an article by Robert Morris.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A theoretical analysis of linear probing was submitted originally by Konheim and Weiss.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] An associative array stores a set of (key, value) pairs and allows insertion, deletion, and lookup (search), with the constraint of unique keys.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In the hash table implementation of associative arrays, an array A of length m is partially filled with n elements, where $m\geq n$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A key **x** is hashed using a hash function h to compute an index location $A[h(x)]$ in the hash table, where $h(x)<m$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The efficiency of a hash table depends on the load factor, defined as the ratio of the number of stored elements to the number of available slots, with lower load factors generally yielding faster operations.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] At this index, both the key and its associated value are stored.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Storing the key alongside the value ensures that lookups can verify the key at the index to retrieve the correct value, even in the presence of collisions.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Under reasonable assumptions, hash tables have better time complexity bounds on search, delete, and insert operations in comparison to self-balancing binary search trees.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hash tables are also commonly used to implement sets, by omitting the stored value for each key and merely tracking whether the key is present.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The performance of the hash table deteriorates in relation to the load factor $\alpha$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In the limit of large m and n , each bucket statistically has a Poisson distribution with expectation $\lambda =\alpha$ for an ideally random hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The software typically ensures that the load factor $\alpha$ remains below a certain constant, $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Therefore, a common approach is to resize or "rehash" the hash table whenever the load factor $\alpha$ reaches $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Similarly the table may also be resized if the load factor drops below $\alpha _{\max }/4$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] With separate chaining hash tables, each slot of the bucket array stores a pointer to a list or array of data.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Separate chaining hash tables suffer gradually declining performance as the load factor grows, and no fixed point beyond which resizing is absolutely needed.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] With separate chaining, the value of $\alpha _{\max }$ that gives best performance is typically between 1 and 3.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] With open addressing, each slot of the bucket array holds exactly one item.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Therefore an open-addressed hash table cannot have a load factor greater than 1.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The performance of open addressing becomes very bad when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Therefore a hash table that uses open addressing *must* be resized or *rehashed* if the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] With open addressing, acceptable figures of max load factor $\alpha _{\max }$ should range around 0.6 to 0.75.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A hash function $h:U\rightarrow \{0,...,m-1\}$ maps the universe U of keys to indices or slots within the table, that is, $h(x)\in \{0,...,m-1\}$ for $x\in U$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The conventional implementations of hash functions are based on the *integer universe assumption* that all elements of the table stem from the universe $U=\{0,...,u-1\}$ , where the bit length of u is confined within the word size of a computer architecture.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A hash function h is said to be perfect for a given set S if it is injective on S , that is, if each element $x\in S$ maps to a different value in ${0,...,m-1}$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A perfect hash function can be created if all the keys are known ahead of time.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The schemes of hashing used in *integer universe assumption* include hashing by division, hashing by multiplication, universal hashing, dynamic perfect hashing, and static perfect hashing.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] However, hashing by division is the commonly used scheme.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by division is as follows: $h(x)\ =\ x\,{\bmod {\,}}m,$ where $h(x)$ is the hash value of $x\in S$ and m is the size of the table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by multiplication is as follows: $h(x)=\lfloor m{\bigl (}(xA){\bmod {1}}{\bigr )}\rfloor$ Where A is a non-integer real-valued constant and m is the size of the table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] An advantage of the hashing by multiplication is that the m is not critical.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Although any value A produces a hash function, Donald Knuth suggests using the golden ratio.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Commonly a string is used as a key to the hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The third edition of *The C++ Programming Language* describes a simple hash function in which an unsigned integer that is initially zero is repeatedly left shifted one bit and then xor'ed with the integer value of the next character.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] This hash value is then taken modulo the table size.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] If the left shift is not circular, then the string length should be at least eight bits less than the size of the unsigned integer in bits.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Another common way to hash a string to an integer is with a polynomial rolling hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Uniform distribution of the hash values is a fundamental requirement of a hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A non-uniform distribution increases the number of collisions and the cost of resolving them.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Uniformity is sometimes difficult to ensure by design, but may be evaluated empirically using statistical tests, e.g., a Pearson's chi-squared test for discrete uniform distributions.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The distribution needs to be uniform only for table sizes that occur in the application.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In particular, if one uses dynamic resizing with exact doubling and halving of the table size, then the hash function needs to be uniform only when the size is a power of two.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Here the index can be computed as some range of bits of the hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] On the other hand, some hashing algorithms prefer to have the size be a prime number.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] For open addressing schemes, the hash function should also avoid *runs*, the mapping of two or more keys to consecutive slots.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Such runs may cause the lookup cost to skyrocket, even if the load factor is low and collisions are infrequent.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The popular multiplicative hash is claimed to have particularly poor run behavior.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] K-independent hashing offers a way to prove a certain hash function does not have bad keysets for a given type of hashtable.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A number of K-independence results are known for collision resolution schemes such as linear probing and cuckoo hashing.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Since K-independence can prove a hash function works, one can then focus on finding the fastest possible such hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A search algorithm that uses hashing consists of two parts.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The first part is computing a hash function which transforms the search key into an array index.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The ideal case is such that no two search keys hash to the same array index.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] However, this is not always the case and impossible to guarantee for unseen given data.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hence the second part of the algorithm is collision resolution.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The two common methods for collision resolution are separate chaining and open addressing.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In separate chaining, the process involves building a linked list with key–value pair for each search array index.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The collided items are chained together through a single linked list, which can be traversed to access the item with a unique search key.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Collision resolution through chaining with linked list is a common method of implementation of hash tables.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] If the element is comparable either numerically or lexically, and inserted into the list by maintaining the total order, it results in faster termination of the unsuccessful searches.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] If the keys are ordered, it could be efficient to use "self-organizing" concepts such as using a self-balancing binary search tree, through which the theoretical worst case could be brought down to $O(\log {n})$ , although it introduces additional complexities.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In dynamic perfect hashing, two-level hash tables are used to reduce the look-up complexity to be a guaranteed $O(1)$ in the worst case.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In this technique, the buckets of k entries are organized as perfect hash tables with $k^{2}$ slots providing constant worst-case lookup time, and low amortized time for insertion.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A study shows array-based separate chaining to be 97% more performant when compared to the standard linked list method under heavy load.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Techniques such as using fusion tree for each buckets also result in constant time for all operations with high probability.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The linked list of separate chaining implementation may not be cache-conscious due to spatial locality—locality of reference—when the nodes of the linked list are scattered across memory, thus the list traversal during insert and search may entail CPU cache inefficiencies.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Open addressing is another collision resolution technique in which every entry record is stored in the bucket array itself, and the hash resolution is performed through **probing**.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] When a new entry has to be inserted, the buckets are examined, starting with the hashed-to slot and proceeding in some *probe sequence*, until an unoccupied slot is found.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] When searching for an entry, the buckets are scanned in the same sequence, until either the target record is found, or an unused array slot is found, which indicates an unsuccessful search.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The performance of open addressing may be slower compared to separate chaining since the probe sequence increases when the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The probing results in an infinite loop if the load factor reaches 1, in the case of a completely filled table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The average cost of linear probing depends on the hash function's ability to distribute the elements uniformly throughout the table to avoid runs, since formation of runs would result in increased search time.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Since the slots are located in successive locations, linear probing could lead to better utilization of CPU cache due to locality of references resulting in reduced memory latency.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Coalesced hashing is a hybrid of both separate chaining and open addressing in which the buckets or nodes link within the table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The algorithm is ideally suited for fixed memory allocation.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The collision in coalesced hashing is resolved by identifying the largest-indexed empty slot on the hash table, then the colliding value is inserted into that slot.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The bucket is also linked to the inserted node's slot which contains its colliding hash address.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Cuckoo hashing is a form of open addressing collision resolution technique which guarantees $O(1)$ worst-case lookup complexity and constant amortized time for insertions.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The collision is resolved through maintaining two hash tables, each having its own hashing function, and collided slot gets replaced with the given item, and the preoccupied element of the slot gets displaced into the other hash table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The process continues until every key has its own spot in the empty buckets of the tables; if the procedure enters into infinite loop—which is identified through maintaining a threshold loop counter—both hash tables get rehashed with newer hash functions and the procedure continues.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hopscotch hashing is an open addressing based algorithm which combines the elements of cuckoo hashing, linear probing and chaining through the notion of a *neighbourhood* of buckets—the subsequent buckets around any given occupied bucket, also called a "virtual" bucket.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The algorithm is designed to deliver better performance when the load factor of the hash table grows beyond 90%; it also provides high throughput in concurrent settings, thus well suited for implementing resizable concurrent hash table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Each bucket within the hash table includes an additional "hop-information"—an *H*-bit bit array for indicating the relative distance of the item which was originally hashed into the current virtual bucket within *H* − 1 entries.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] *H* − 1, subsequent swap and hop-info bit array manipulation of each bucket is performed in accordance with its neighbourhood invariant properties.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Robin Hood hashing is an open addressing based collision resolution algorithm; the collisions are resolved through favouring the displacement of the element that is farthest—or longest *probe sequence length* (PSL)—from its "home location" i.e. the bucket to which the item was hashed into.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] It is named after Robin Hood, a mythical heroic outlaw who stole from the rich to give to the poor.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Although Robin Hood hashing does not change the theoretical search cost, it significantly affects the variance of the distribution of the items on the buckets, i.e. dealing with long run formation in the hash table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Each node within the hash table that uses Robin Hood hashing should be augmented to store an extra PSL value.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] If a hash table becomes "too empty" after deleting some elements, resizing may be performed to avoid excessive memory usage.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Generally, a new hash table with a size double that of the original hash table gets allocated privately and every item in the original hash table gets moved to the newly allocated one by computing the hash values of the items followed by the insertion operation.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Rehashing is simple, but computationally expensive.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Some hash table implementations, notably in real-time systems, cannot pay the price of enlarging the hash table all at once, because it may interrupt time-critical operations.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] If one cannot avoid dynamic resizing, a solution is to perform the resizing gradually to avoid storage blip—typically at 50% of new table's size—during rehashing and to avoid memory fragmentation that triggers heap compaction due to deallocation of large memory blocks caused by the old hash table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In such case, the rehashing operation is done incrementally through extending prior memory block allocated for the old hash table such that the buckets of the hash table remain unaltered.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A common approach for amortized rehashing involves maintaining two hash functions $h_{\text{old}}$ and $h_{\text{new}}$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Linear hashing is an implementation of the hash table which enables dynamic growths or shrinks of the table one bucket at a time.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The performance of a hash table is dependent on the hash function's ability in generating quasi-random numbers ( $\sigma$ ) for entries in the hash table where K , n and $h(x)$ denotes the key, number of buckets and the hash function such that $\sigma \ =\ h(K)\ \%\ n$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] If the hash function generates the same $\sigma$ for distinct keys ( $K_{1}\neq K_{2},\ h(K_{1})\ =\ h(K_{2})$ ), this results in *collision*, which is dealt with in a variety of ways.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The constant time complexity ( $O(1)$ ) of the operation in a hash table is presupposed on the condition that the hash function doesn't generate colliding indices; thus, the performance of the hash table is directly proportional to the chosen hash function's ability to disperse the indices.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] However, construction of such a hash function is practically infeasible, that being so, implementations depend on case-specific collision resolution techniques in achieving higher performance.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] The best performance is obtained in the case that the hash function distributes the elements of the universe uniformaly, and the elements stored at the table are drawn at random from the universe.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In this case, in hashing with chaining, the expected time for a successful search is ${\textstyle 1+{\frac {\alpha }{2}}+\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ , and the expected time for an unsuccessful search is ${\textstyle e^{-\alpha }+\alpha +\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hash tables are commonly used to implement many types of in-memory tables.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] They are used to implement associative arrays.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hash tables may also be used as disk-based data structures and database indices (such as in dbm) although B-trees are more popular in these applications.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hash tables can be used to implement caches, auxiliary data tables that are used to speed up the access to data that is primarily stored in slower media.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] In this application, hash collisions can be handled by discarding one of the two colliding entries—usually erasing the old item that is currently stored in the table and overwriting it with the new item, so every item in the table has a unique hash value.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Hash tables can be used in the implementation of set data structure, which can store unique values without any particular order; set is typically used in testing the membership of a value in the collection, rather than element retrieval.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] A transposition table to a complex Hash Table which stores information about each section that has been searched.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/hash-table] Many programming languages provide hash table functionality, either as built-in associative arrays or as standard library modules.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The file structure of a dynamic hashing data structure adapts itself to changes in the size of the file, so expensive periodic file reorganization is avoided.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] A Linear Hashing file expands by splitting a predetermined bucket into two and shrinks by merging two predetermined buckets into one.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The trigger for a reconstruction depends on the flavor of the scheme; it could be an overflow at a bucket or load factor (i.e., the number of records divided by the number of buckets) moving outside of a predetermined range.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] In Linear Hashing there are two types of buckets, those that are to be split and those already split.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] While extendible hashing splits only overflowing buckets, spiral hashing (a.k.a. spiral storage) distributes records unevenly over the buckets such that buckets with high costs of insertion, deletion, or retrieval are earliest in line for a split.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Linear Hashing has also been made into a scalable distributed data structure, **LH***.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] In LH*, each bucket resides at a different server.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] LH* itself has been expanded to provide data availability in the presence of failed buckets.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Key based operations (inserts, deletes, updates, reads) in LH and LH* take maximum constant time independent of the number of buckets and hence of records.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Records in LH or LH* consists of a key and a content, the latter basically all the other attributes of the record.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] For example, in Ellis' implementation, a bucket is a linked list of records.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The file allows the key based CRUD operations create or insert, read, update, and delete as well as a scan operations that scans all records, for example to do a database select operation on a non-key attribute.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Records are stored in buckets whose numbering starts with 0.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The key distinction from schemes such as Fagin's extendible hashing is that as the file expands due to insertions, only one bucket is split at a time, and the order in which buckets are split is already predetermined.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The hash function $h_{i}(c)$ returns the 0-based index of the bucket that contains the record with key c .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] When a bucket which uses the hash function $h_{i}$ is split into two new buckets, the hash function $h_{i}$ is replaced with $h_{i+1}$ for both of those new buckets.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] At any time, at most two hash functions $h_{l}$ and $h_{l+1}$ are used; such that l corresponds to the current **level**.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The family of hash functions $h_{i}(c)$ is also referred to as the dynamic hash function.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Typically, the value of i in $h_{i}$ corresponds to the number of rightmost binary digits of the key c that are used to segregate the buckets.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] This dynamic hash function can be expressed arithmetically as ${\textstyle h_{i}(c)\mapsto (c{\bmod {2}}^{i})}$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Note that when the total number of buckets is equal to one, $i=0$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Complete the calculations below to determine the correct hashing function for the given hashing key c .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Linear hashing algorithms may use only controlled splits or both controlled and uncontrolled splits.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] An **uncontrolled split** occurs when a split is performed whenever a bucket overflows, in which case that bucket would be split into two separate buckets.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The index of the next bucket to be split is part of the file state and called the **split pointer** s .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The split pointer corresponds to the first bucket that uses the hash function $h_{l}$ instead of $h_{l+1}$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] For example, if numerical records are inserted into the hash index according to their farthest right binary digits, the bucket corresponding with the appended bucket will be split.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Thus, if we have the buckets labelled as 000, 001, 10, 11, 100, 101, we would split the bucket 10 because we are appending and creating the next sequential bucket 110.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] When a bucket is split, split pointer and possibly the level are updated according to the following, such that the level is 0 when the linear hashing index only has 1 bucket.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The main contribution of LH* is to allow a client of an LH* file to find the bucket where the record resides even if the client does not know the file state.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Clients in fact store their version of the file state, which is initially just the knowledge of the first bucket, namely Bucket 0.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Based on their file state, a client calculates the address of a key and sends a request to that bucket.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] At the bucket, the request is checked and if the record is not at the bucket, it is forwarded.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] In a reasonably stable system, that is, if there is only one split or merge going on while the request is processed, it can be shown that there are at most two forwards.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] After a forward, the final bucket sends an Image Adjustment Message to the client whose state is now closer to the state of the distributed file.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] The file state consists of split pointer s and level l .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Griswold and Townsend discussed the adoption of linear hashing in the Icon language.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] They discussed the implementation alternatives of dynamic array algorithm used in linear hashing, and presented performance comparisons using a list of Icon benchmark applications.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/linear-hashing] Linear hashing is used in the Berkeley database system (BDB), which in turn is used by many software systems, using a C implementation derived from the CACM article and first published on the Usenet in 1988 by Esmond Pitt.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/spiral-hashing] Spiral hashing requires a uniform hash function of the keys of the records into the unit interval $[0,1]$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/spiral-hashing] If the hash file starts at bucket S , the key k is mapped into a real number $x=S+h(k)\in [S,S+1]$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/spiral-hashing] The final address is then computed as $\lfloor d^{x}\rfloor$ where d is the "extension factor".
[src:dynamic-hash-index/spiral-hashing] When S is incremented, approximately d new buckets are created on the right.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/spiral-hashing] Larson conducted experiments that showed that Linear hashing still had superior performance over Spiral Hashing.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Since static hashing requires that the database, its objects, and reference remain the same, its applications are limited.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Databases which contain information which changes rarely are also eligible as it would only require a full rehash of the entire database on rare occasion.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Examples of this include sets of words and definitions of specific languages, sets of significant data for an organization's personnel, etc.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Perfect hashing is a model of hashing in which any set of n elements can be stored in a hash table of equal size and can have lookups done in constant time.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] It was specifically discovered and discussed by Fredman, Komlos and Szemeredi (1984) and has therefore been nicknamed "FKS hashing".
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] FKS hashing makes use of a hash table with two levels in which the top level contains n buckets which each contain their own hash table.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] FKS hashing requires that if collisions occur they must do so only on the top level.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] The top level contains a randomly created hash function, $h(x)$ , which fits within the constraints of a Carter and Wegman hash function from universal hashing.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Having done so the top level shall contain n buckets labeled $k_{1},k_{2},k_{3},...,k_{n}$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Following this pattern, all of the buckets hold a hash table of size $s_{i}$ and a respective hash function $h_{i}(x)$ .
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] The hash function will be decided by setting $s_{i}$ to $k_{i}^{2}$ and randomly going through functions until there are no collisions.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Because there are $n \choose 2$ pairs of elements, of which have a probability of collision equal to $1/n$ , FKS hashing can expect to have strictly less than $n/2$ collisions.
[src:dynamic-hash-index/static-hashing] Based on this fact and that each $h(x)$ was selected so that the number of collisions would be at most $n/2$ , the size of each table on the lower level will be no greater than $2n$ .
